  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has several key milestones:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initial anti-money laundering efforts emerged in the 1920s targeting organized crime\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) first established reporting requirements for financial transactions\n- Comprehensive Drug Abuse Prevention and Control Act (1970) introduced initial anti-money laundering provisions\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) formally criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n\n3. International Efforts:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- Proliferation of international anti-money laundering standards and cooperation\n\n4. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing prevention\n- Enhanced international information sharing mechanisms\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Framework:\n- Comprehensive global regulatory infrastructure\n- Increasing complexity of financial tracking technologies\n- Ongoing efforts to address cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n\nThese developments reflect an evolutionary legal approach to combating financial crimes.",
